The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Kotak Bank rejig of arms passes muster

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 Mumbai, July 20: The board of Kotak Mahindra Bank Ltd has approved the restructuring of its two subsidiaries ? Kotak Mahindra Capital Company Ltd and Kotak Mahindra Securities Ltd.

 The board has approved the demerger of the trading and principal division of Kotak Mahindra Capital Company (KMCC), which includes the primary dealership division, into Kotak Mahindra Bank.

 The trading and clearing operations and strategic investments of Kotak Mahindra Securities Ltd will also be demerged into KMCC.

 The board has also decided to convert the five indirect subsidiaries to direct subsidiaries of the bank. These arms are Kotak Mahindra Securities Ltd, Kotak Mahindra (International) Ltd, Kotak Mahindra (UK) Ltd, Kotak Mahindra Inc and Global Investment Opportunities Fund Ltd.

 Meanwhile, Kotak Mahindra Bank has reported a 21 per cent increase in its profit after tax at Rs 23.91 crore for the first quarter of the current fiscal against Rs 19.68 crore in the same period last fiscal.

 The profit after tax has been calculated after considering an additional provision of Rs 2.96 crore on standard assets and a provision of Rs 5.06 crore on account of liability for employee benefits. 

 Total income of the bank increased by over 73 per cent to Rs 306.52 crore for the quarter from Rs 176.73 crore in the year-ago period.

 Net interest income was Rs 111.41 crore, up 61 per cent from Rs 69.30 crore in the year-ago period, while other income went up by 78 per cent to Rs 64.29 crore.

 The deposits of the bank stood at Rs 7,648.93 crore on June 30, up 57 per cent from Rs 4,881.86 crore. Advances grew by 67 per cent to Rs 7,251.53 crore on June 30. Capital adequacy ratio of the bank was 14.66 per cent against 12.52 per cent on June 30, 2005.

 On a consolidated basis, profit after tax for the quarter increased by 125 per cent to Rs 104.43 crore from Rs 46.47 crore in the year-ago period.

 The consolidated total income increased by 70 per cent to Rs 776.58 crore from Rs 455.51 crore last year. The consolidated fee income increased 87 per cent to Rs 367.85 crore from Rs 196.68 crore last year.

 According to the bank, securities broking income, fees from investment banking, fees on distribution of financial products and premium income from life insurance business contributed to the growth in fee income.

 Union Bank 

 The Union Bank has registered a 30 per cent drop in net profit at Rs 166.81 crore for the quarter ended June 30, 2006, compared with Rs 240.39 crore for the quarter ended June 30, 2005. Total income has increased from Rs 1,491.45 crore in the first quarter of the financial year 2005-06 to Rs 1,830.72 crore for the same quarter this year. The operating profit for the quarter stood at Rs 426.48 crore.




